  "bib_entries": {
    "12038713": {
      "title": "Different migration patterns of sea urchin and mouse sperm revealed by a microfluidic chemotaxis device",
      "abstract": "Chemotaxis refers to a process whereby cells move up or down a chemical gradient. Sperm chemotaxis is known to be a strategy exploited by marine invertebrates such as sea urchins to reach eggs efficiently in moving water. Less is understood about how or whether chemotaxis is used by mammalian sperm to reach eggs, where fertilization takes place within the confinement of a reproductive tract. In this report, we quantitatively assessed sea urchin and mouse sperm chemotaxis using a recently developed microfluidic model and high-speed imaging. Results demonstrated that sea urchin Arbacia punctulata sperm were chemotactic toward the peptide resact with high chemotactic sensitivity, with an average velocity Vx up the chemical gradient as high as 20% of its average speed (238 μm/s), while mouse sperm displayed no statistically significant chemotactic behavior in progesterone gradients, which had been proposed to guide mammalian sperm toward eggs. This work demonstrates the validity of a microfluidic model for quantitative sperm chemotaxis studies, and reveals a biological insight that chemotaxis up a progesterone gradient may not be a universal strategy for mammalian sperm to reach eggs."
    },
    "87181483": {
      "title": "The shedding reaction in Arbacia punctulata",
      "abstract": "IT HAS been the custom for twenty-five years and perhaps longer to obtain eggs and sperm from the sea urchin by cutting horizontally through the test or by removing the lantern. If animals cut in this way are placed aboral side down in a watch glass, the eggs or sperm are at once extruded through the five genital pores. No one has investigated the question as to just why injury invariably results in the shedding of the genital products. In view of recent developments in the field of humoral physiology, it is of considerable interest to determine whether this specific reaction is of humoral or neural origin. The object of the present investigation is to determine the nature of the stimulation which causes sea urchins to spawn when injured. Solution of this problem might indicate possible relationships to invertebrate stimulation in general."
    }
  },
